            "creation_date": 1381175378,
            "body": "<p>how about<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>if(total &gt;= 100)\n{\n    //use 50%\n}\nelse if(total &gt;= 50)\n{\n    //use 40%\n}\nelse if(total &gt;= 20)\n{\n    //use 30%\n}\nelse if(total &gt;= 10)\n{\n    //use 20%\n}\nelse\n{\n    //no discount\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you reach the else if for <code>total &gt;= 50<\/code>, you already know that <code>total &lt; 100<\/code>. and so on. This is really what makes use of a good <code>if..else if..else<\/code> statement, when you can infer conditions based on the previous statements. Your code right now would be equivalent if you used just if statements. <\/p>\n\n<p>Also<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>total = (((x*99) - (x * 99)* .2));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>would be better written as<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>total = x * 99 * (1-.2)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 19233379,
            "question_id": 19233234,
            "last_edit_date": 1381175918
        },
        {
            "owner": {
